title: By Adverse Winds. [A novel.]
author: Smeaton, William Henry Oliphant.
snippet: Aweel, I've been drivin' her aboot synhalf aifter eleeven, seekin' her freens, and they're a' awa'. We've been tae Scotland Street, and tae Eton Terrace, and noohere, but deil a ane—excoose me, miss—no' ane can we getava. She wants me tae drive her oot tae Allensmuir, whaurshe stops, whilk I wad dae instantly, for I'm a faither masel',and it waes me sairly tae leave the bonny bit thing i' thestreets, but ma beastie is fair foondered wi' the day's wark,and winna gang a fit-length mair."

title: By Adverse Winds. [A novel.]
author: Smeaton, William Henry Oliphant.
snippet: But as we did not get intill after eleven, I thought I would go to my aunt's in ScotlandStreet. But she had removed to Eton Terrace. I went thereto find the house shut up, just like this one.
